 

 1. What is the difference between INNER JOIN and LEFT JOIN?

 	INNER JOIN returns only matching rows from both tables based on the ON condition—non-matches from either side get excluded completely. LEFT JOIN (LEFT OUTER JOIN) returns all rows from the left table plus matching rows from the right table; non-matching right rows fill with NULLs in right columns. INNER JOIN = intersection; LEFT JOIN = left table fully preserved.

 
 2. Can we join more than two tables using INNER JOIN? How?

 	Yes, chain INNER JOINs across unlimited tables sequentially—each new JOIN builds on prior results. Syntax: FROM table1 t1 INNER JOIN table2 t2 ON t1.id = t2.t1_id INNER JOIN table3 t3 ON t2.id = t3.t2_id. Example: SELECT e.name, d.dept_name, proj.title FROM employees e INNER JOIN departments d ON e.dept_id = d.id INNER JOIN projects proj ON e.proj_id = proj.id links employee-department-projects. Use table aliases for clarity; optimizer handles join order efficiently.

 
 3. What happens when there are no matching records in an INNER JOIN?

 	When no matches exist, INNER JOIN returns zero rows—the entire result set empties since no pairs satisfy the ON condition. Example: Customers without Orders yields nothing, unlike LEFT JOIN (all customers + NULL order columns). This filtering behavior makes INNER JOIN precise for confirmed relationships but risky for incomplete data audits.


 4. Why is INNER JOIN faster than OUTER JOIN in some cases?

 	INNER JOIN often runs faster because it produces smaller result sets (only matches), allowing optimizers to prune unnecessary rows early via indexes and skip NULL-handling overhead of OUTER JOINs. With restrictive ON conditions and good indexes, fewer rows mean less I/O, sorting, and temp space; OUTER JOINs must preserve all left/right rows regardless, bloating intermediate results. Benchmark difference grows with large tables.​


 5. Can INNER JOIN be used without the ON clause? If yes, how?

 	No, INNER JOIN requires an ON clause (or deprecated WHERE-equivalent comma syntax) to specify matching logic—FROM t1 INNER JOIN t2 alone fails with syntax errors in modern SQL. Old-style theta joins used FROM t1, t2 WHERE t1.id = t2.id (implicit INNER), but explicit INNER JOIN ... ON is standard, readable, and optimizer-friendly. Without conditions, it acts like CROSS JOIN (Cartesian explosion—avoid!).​





